[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted
[normal] by [bold]Steven J. Rosen
[normal] Director, The Washington project of the Middle East Forum 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Over 63 years,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]UNRWA has become an agency that perpetuates the refugee problem rather than 
[normal]contributing to its resolution.
[normal]UNRWA does not work to settle refugees; instead, by registering each day ever more grandchildren and great-grandchildren who have never been displaced from their homes or employment, artificially adding them to the tally of
[normal] “refugees,” it adds to number of refugees nursing grievances. By now, these descendants comprise over 90 percent of UNRWA refugees.
[normal]Further, UNRWA violates the Refugee Convention by insisting that nearly two million people who have been given citizenship
[normal] in Jordan, Syria and Lebanon (and who constitute 40% of UNRWA’s beneficiaries) are still refugees.
[normal]As a result of such practices, instead of going down through resettlement and natural attrition, the number of UNRWA refugees has steadily grown since 1949
[normal], from 750,000 to almost 5 million. At this rate, UNRWA refugees will exceed 8 million by 2030 and 20 million by 2060, its camps and schools endlessly promoting the futile dream that these millions of descendants someday will “return” to their ancestors’ h
[normal]omes in Israel. When even Palestinian Authority chairman Mahmoud Abbas acknowledges that sending five million Palestinians would mean “the end of Israel,” it’s clear that UNRWA obstructs conflict resolution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Can the elements of UNRWA useful to Israel be 
[normal]retained without perpetuating the refugee status? Yes, but this requires distinguishing UNRWA’s role as a social service agency from its role producing ever-more refugees.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Section III.A.2 and Section III.B of UNRWA’s Consolidated Eligibility &amp; Registration
[normal] Instructions allow it to provide social services to Palestinians without defining them as refugees. 
[normal]UNRWA donors, starting with the United Kingdom, should stop being accomplices to UNRWA’s perpetuation of the refugee status.
[normal]The U.K.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]should treat UNRWA
[normal] as a vehicle to deliver social services, nothing more. It should insist that UNRWA beneficiaries who either were never displaced or who already have citizenship in other countries, although perhaps eligible for UNRWA services, are not refugees. Establishi
[normal]ng this distinction reduces a key irritant in Arab-Israeli relations.
[normal]Submission[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal](1) 
[normal]Led by the 
[normal]United States
[normal],
[normal] t
[normal]he 
[normal]founders of the United Nations Relief and Works Administration (UNRWA), the agency tasked with oversight of the 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] refugees
[normal], conce
[normal]ived 
[normal]of it as a 
[normal]temporary 
[normal]instrument to help 
[normal]relieve the plight of 
[normal]the Arab refugees displa
[normal]ced by the struggle over 
[normal]Israel
[normal]’
[normal]s creation in 1948.
[normal] 
[normal]But over the ensuing sixty
[normal]-three years,
[normal] UNRWA has evolved into an agency that perpetuates the refugee 
[normal]problem as 
[normal]a source of conflict
[normal] rather than contributing to its resolution.
[normal] 
[normal]Its refugee camps and educational programs keep alive the impossible dream that millions of descendants
[normal] of the original refugees will “return” to today’
[normal]s 
[normal]Israel
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Its social service delivery 
[normal]programs create permanent dependency and impede local integration into the societies and countries where its beneficiaries have resided for decades.
[normal] 
[normal]Unlike its sister agency, the United Nations High Commission for Refugees (UNHCR)
[normal],
[normal] which is responsible for
[normal] millions of non-Palestinian refugees worldwide, it does not have an active program 
[normal]for “local integration” of 
[normal]refugees where they now reside nor 
[normal]“resettlement” 
[normal]in third countries.
[normal] This special issue will explore the extent to which it has complied with it
[normal]s original mandate and ways and means for its reform.
[normal](2) I
[normal]t was not always the case that UNRWA 
[normal]stood in the way of local integration and 
[normal]res
[normal]ettlement. 
[normal]In 
[normal]its 
[normal]early years
[normal], 
[normal]particularly from 1949 to 1960,
[normal] 
[normal]UNRWA
[normal] 
[normal]followed a 
[normal]declared policy of 
[normal]“reintegration”
[normal] of Palestinian refugees into the normal life of the Middle East, a term understood to include resettling large numbers of 
[normal]them 
[normal]outside 
[normal]Israel
[normal](3) UNRWA’s reintegration program was endorsed by U.N.
[normal] General Assembly Resolut
[normal]ion 393 (V)
[normal], enacted
[normal] on December 2,
[normal] 
[normal]1950
[normal]. It called for “
[normal]the reintegration of the refugees into the economic life of the 
[normal]Near East
[normal], either by repatriation or resettlement
[normal],” which “
[normal]is essential in preparation for the time when international assistance is no
[normal] longer available, and for the realization of conditions of 
[normal]peace and stability in the area.” The resolution also instructed UNRWA “
[normal]to establish a reintegration fund
[normal] ... 
[normal]for the permanent re-establishment of refugees and their removal from relief
[normal].”
[normal](4) In
[normal] November 1951,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]UNRWA’
[normal]s second director
[normal], John Blandford, Jr., 
[normal]proposed a three
[normal]-year, $200 million program to r
[normal]eintegrate 150,000–200,000 refugees into their Arab host countries.
[normal] Blandford’s plan
[normal] was endorsed by U
[normal].
[normal]N
[normal].
[normal] General Assembly
[normal] 
[normal]Reso
[normal]lution
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]513
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]of Janu
[normal]ary 26, 1952, which tasked 
[normal]UNRWA 
[normal]“
[normal]to explore with the governments
[normal] 
[normal]...
[normal] 
[normal]their assuming administration of reintegration project
[normal]s at the earliest possible date.”
[normal] Seven years later, t
[normal]he 
[normal]concept was reaffirmed by U
[normal].
[normal]N
[normal].
[normal] secretary general Dag Hammarskjold, 
[normal]who cal
[normal]led for the “r
[normal]eintegration
[normal]”
[normal] of refugees 
[normal]“
[normal]into the economic life of the area.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal](7) 
[normal]Today, neither UNRWA
[normal]’s
[normal] 
[normal]“Medium Term Strategy 2010-
[normal]2015
[normal],”
[normal] nor the official “Framework for Cooperation b
[normal]etween UNRWA and the Government of the United States,
[normal]”
[normal] mention reintegration
[normal] at all, nor do 
[normal]c
[normal]ongressional appropriations of funds for UNRWA 
[normal]make allocations for r
[normal]eintegration as they did in earlier years
[normal].
[normal](8) 
[normal]Former UNRWA general
[normal] 
[normal]counsel
[normal] James G. Lindsay 
[normal]remarked
[normal] that 
[normal]“
[normal]neither the donors nor the General
[normal] Assem
[normal]bly has pressed UNRWA on ‘reintegration’
[normal] in quite some time.
[normal]”
[normal] Lance Bartholomeus
[normal]z, 
[normal]former head 
[normal]of the
[normal] 
[normal]International
[normal] Law Division of UNRWA, said, “
[normal]This part of the mandate probably e
[normal]nded by 1960 when reference to ‘reintegration’
[normal] was dropped from General As
[normal]sembly resolutions relating to UNRWA, reflecting some acknowledgment that this objective had been defeated.
[normal]”
[normal] And 
[normal]Peter Hansen, former commissioner g
[normal]eneral of UNRWA, said in 2004, “
[normal]The 
[normal]a
[normal]gency
[normal]’
[normal]s mandate has repeatedly been refined and shaped by other Genera
[normal]l Assembly resolutions, which have allowed it to shift its focus from reintegration efforts in its early years to human development projects through to this very day.
[normal]”
[normal](9) And so UNRWA abandoned its original mission of relief extension and conflict resolu
[normal]tion, evolving into an agency for the perpetuation of unsettled claims against 
[normal]Israel
[normal] for millions of persons born in the years attending the founding of 
[normal]Israel
[normal] in 1948.
[normal](10) 
[normal]At its inception 
[normal]on May 1, 
[normal]1950, UNRWA served 
[normal]approximately 750,000 persons whom it considered 
[normal]Palestine
[normal] refugees. 
[normal]Due to natural attrition, many of those original refugees are no longer alive today
[normal] 
[normal]and shou
[normal]ld have been removed from UNRWA’
[normal]s registra
[normal]tion rolls. Yet the number of “refugees”
[normal] now registered with UNRWA has grown expone
[normal]ntially instead of 
[normal]declining, with 
[normal]almost 5,000,000 persons registered 
[normal]as 
[normal]Palestinian refugees
[normal]—
[normal]seven times as many as 
[normal]those 
[normal]registered 
[normal]sixty-two years ago
[normal].
[normal](11) 
[normal]This 
[normal]has been made 
[normal]possible 
[normal]through the addition of 
[normal]descendants of refugees 
[normal](
[normal]along the male line) to 
[normal]UNRWA’s 
[normal]refugee rolls, regardless of how much time has passed.
[normal] 
[normal]Today, the 
[normal]vast 
[normal]majority of tho
[normal]se classified by UNRWA as Palestinian refugees
[normal] are in fact descendants of refugees, not persons who were ever ref
[normal]ugees themselves.
[normal] 
[normal]These are grandchildren and great-grandchildren born in 
[normal]Jordan
[normal], the West 
[normal]Bank, 
[normal]Gaza
[normal], 
[normal]Lebanon
[normal], and 
[normal]Syria
[normal]—
[normal]not in pre-194
[normal]8 
[normal]Palestine
[normal].
[normal](12) According to a projection published by the United Nations High Commission for Refugees extrapolating f
[normal]rom UNRWA’s past growth rates, by 2030 UNRWA’s refugee list will expand another 70 percent to 8.5 million.
[normal] In fact, at the same growth rate, by 2060 there will be 
[normal]four times
[normal] as many Palestinian refugees as there are today and
[normal] twenty five times 
[normal]the number 
[normal]registered by UNRWA in 1950—though none of the original Palestinian refugees are likely to be alive by then.
