[normal](19) 
[normal]The United 
[normal]Kingdom
[normal] is a signatory to and a strong supporter of the 1951 Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees
[normal], as are 143 other nations
[normal].
[normal]  
[normal]That convention 
[normal]states
[normal] that a person s
[normal]hall no longer be considered
[normal] a refugee
[normal] if 
[normal]“
[normal](3) He has acquired a new nationality
[normal] 
[normal]and enjoys the protection of the country of his new nationality.
[normal]”
[normal] 
[normal]The United Nations High Commission on Refugees
[normal] (UNHCR)
[normal], charged with implement
[normal]ing 
[normal]the refugee convention for all refugees in the world o
[normal]ther than 
[normal]those 
[normal]Palestinians covered by UNRWA, is guided by this principle
[normal] as is the European Union, which 
[normal]provides that 
[normal]a “
[normal]third country national or a stateless person shall cease to be a refugee, if he or she:
[normal] 
[normal]...
[normal] 
[normal](c) 
[normal]has
[normal] acquired a new nationality, and
[normal] enjoys the protection of the country of his or her new nationality
[normal].”
[normal] When UNHCR refugees get citizenship in another country, they are taken off its list. But when UNRWA “refugees” get new citizenships, they are still considered refugees.
[normal](20) Most 
[normal]recipi
[normal]ents of UNRWA services in 
[normal]Jordan
[normal] have been given citizenship in that country
[normal],
[normal] 
